\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 DicePlus}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par Some values that you edit are called DICEPLUS fields. This means that they are text fields which let you specify the actual value in typical ADnD dice terms. 
\par 
\par Some valid examples:
\par 
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 1d20
\par 1d4 + 2
\par 10
\par 5 + level * 3
\par 1d4 + 2 * level
\par 3d6 + 2 * Elf
\par (dexterity == 18) * "Cleric/Fighter" * level
\par }{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par A DICEPLUS field is evaluated using the usual mathmatical operator precedence. A typical way to specify a value in ADnD is to state '1 die 4 plus 3 per level' which on paper is represented as '1d4 + 3/level'. In DICEPLUS format this would be '1d4+3*level'
. The '/' is treated as mathematical division rather than a concept of 'per level'. In order of evaluation, this expression can be stated as
\par 
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab  get current character level
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab  multiply level by 3
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab  roll 1d4
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab  add the two results together
\par 
\par You can use parentheses to specify the order in which the terms are evaluated. (1d4+3)*level can be different than 1d4+(3*level).
\par 
\par A DICEPLUS field can contain keywords that are evaluated at runtime. For instance, '1d4+3*level' will evaluate 'level' to be a character's current level and then multiply that by 3. 
\par 
\par To specify a random dice roll, use the XdY syntax, where
\par 
\par xdy: x=num dice, 'd' is a keyword, y is num sides on each dice. 
\par 
\par Example: 1d4 for 1 die 4
\par 
\par These are the mathematical operators allowed in a DICEPLUS expression.
\par 
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par '+' : addition
\par '-' : subtraction
\par '*' : multiplication
\par '/' : division
\par '==' : equality
\par '!=' : not equal
\par '>' : greater than
\par '>=' : greater than or equal to
\par '<' : greater than
\par '<=' : greater than or equal to
\par '&' : bitwise AND
\par '&&' : logical AND
\par '|' : bitwise OR
\par '||' : logical OR
\par '^' : bitwise exclusive OR
\par '^^' : logical exclusive OR
\par '%' : MOD
\par }{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par You can also use unary '-' and '+' to specify the sign of a number, such as '-1' for negative one.
\par 
\par There are several possible keyword 
types allowed in a DICEPLUS expression. They are evaluated at runtime in the context of the currently active character. You can use a race name, class name, skill name, or the literals 'level', 'class', 'race', 'male', and 'female'. These keywords are not
 
case-sensitive. Some keywords have the '-' or '/' tokens in them, such as 'Half-Elf' and 'Cleric/Fighter'. In such situations you must enclose the keyword in quotes, as in '1d4 + "Half-Elf"'. If you do not, then the '-' and '/' tokens will be interpreted 
as the mathmatical operators subtraction and division. To be recognized as a token for which runtime substitution can be made, the race/class/skill keywords must match one of the defined values in your races.txt, baseclass.txt, or ability.txt files. 

\par 
\par If portions of the DICEPLUS expression cannot be understood, those portions will be ignored. An expression such as '10 + jerk * 11' will always be 10 because the 'jerk * 11' cannot be understood. 
\par 
\par You can limit the final result of a DICEPLUS expression by usin
g '|<' to specify minimum, or '>|' to specify maximum. Example: '1d4+2 |< 2 >| 9'. That will limit the '1d4+2' to a minimum of 2 and maximum of 9. You can write the same expression as '2 |< 1d4+2 >| 9'. The default limit is -999 to 999, and this default i
s not normally displayed. If you enter a different limit from the default it will always be displayed in a DICEPLUS expression.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb50\sa50\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \page }{\cs18\super\insrsid5405\charrsid5405 ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
