\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Extending Logic Block}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Very complicated functions will require more than one Logic Block Event to calculate.
\par 
\par Let us say that you want to know if party leader has a strength greater than 13, is older than 22 years, is a fighter or a thief, and is carrying a Axe of Beheading.
\par 
\par In general, you can carry out two "AND" operations in each Logic Block Event.  So the strategy is to compute the result in pieces, setting a temporary attribute that can be tested in a later Logic Event.  Here is how it might be done:
\par 
\par First Event --
\par Input-B set to Ability Score ("0,Strength").  Input-A set to Literal ("13").  Gate-C set to Arithmetic greater.
\par Input-F set to Age ("0").  Input-D set to Literal ("22").  Gate-J set to Arithmetic Greater.
\par Gate-L set to Logical And.
\par This gets the strength and age of character 0 and compares them with the constants 13 and 22.
\par First Action (Always) Set Temporary Attribute ("Strength/Age OK=&L")
\par This sets the attribute "Strength/Age OK" to "1" if both the strength AND the age criteria are met.
\par 
\par Chain (Normal Chain) to another Logic Block
\par 
\par Second Event --
\par Input-A set to Character Class ("0").  Input-B set to Literal("Thief").  Input-F set to Literal("Fighter").  Gate-E and Gate-J both set to String Equal.  Gate-L set to Logical OR.
\par This will provide a true output from Gate-L if the character 0 is either a Fighter or a Thief.
\par First Action (Always) Set Temporary Attribute ("Class OK=&L").
\par This sets the attribute "Class OK" to a 1 if the character is the proper class.
\par 
\par Chain (Normal Chain) to another Logic Block
\par 
\par Third Event --
\par Input-A set to Temporary Attribute ("Class OK").
\par Input-B set to Temporary Attribute ("Strength/Age OK").
\par Gate-C set to Logical AND.
\par Input-F set to Item List("0") to get items held by character zero.
\par Input-D set to Literal("/Axe of Beheading/").
\par Gate-J set to GREP.  This asks if the Axe is in the list.
\par Gate-L set to Logical AND.
\par 
\par This final result will be true if the character is a fighter or thief, is over 22 years of age, has a strength greater than 13, and is carrying the Axe of Beheading.
\par 
\par "AND" operations can also be done by chaining only if results are true.  "OR" operations are probably more easily done with the temporary attribute method.
\par 
