\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Logic Block Inputs}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Each of the fiv
e inputs is identical and produces a character string (text).  The source of the string depends on the "input-type" and possibly an "input-parameter".  The parameter field may contain references of the form &A through &L.  These references are replaced wi
t
h the text from the input or gate labeled with that letter.  The inputs, gates, and parameters are evaluated in alphabetical order so that it makes sense for the parameter in Input-D to reference &B but not the other way around because at the time paramet
er B is evaluated Input-D has not yet been computed.
\par 
\par Here are the Input Types along with an explanation of the parameter associated with each:
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Literal}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The resulting string is whatever you type into the parameter field.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Global ASL}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter names a global }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Associated String List (ASL) Entry}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(Associated String Lists)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
.  The resulting string is the value associated with that key in the global ASL.  If no such entry exists then the result is an empty string.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Party Size}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The result is a decimal number giving the number of characters in the party.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Party ASL}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter names a party }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Associated String List (ASL) Entry}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(Associated String Lists)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
.  The resulting string is the value associated with that key in the party's ASL.  If no such entry exists then the result is an empty string.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Item List}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter is the number of a party member.  The first member is zero, the second is one, etc.  Each items in that member's possession is added to the result in the form "slash item-name slash item-number slash".  For example:
\par     }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 /Axe of Rain/0//Key of G/1//Toothbrush/2/}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Character Info}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par This function is deprecated.  The information about characters can be more easily gooten using the "Character Attribute" functions which are discussed a few inches down this page.
\par 
\par No parameter.  The result is an enormous string with information about all the characters in the party.  The format is:
\par    }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 /first character//second character//third character/  etc}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par Each character's information is encoded as semi-colon delimited, tagged fields.  For example:
\par      }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 name=Richard;age=89;STR=12;AC=2;}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par Note that the last field has a semi-colon to make it easier to do string searches.
\par So a complete string would be of the form:
\par    }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 /name=Paul;age=7;//name=Kevin;age=25//name=Alex;age=17;/ }{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The following fields are currently included:
\par    name
\par    pos
\par    THAC0
\par    AC
\par    age
\par    maxage
\par    HP
\par    maxHP
\par    enc
\par    maxenc
\par    maxmove
\par    STR
\par    INT
\par    WIS
\par    DEX
\par    CON
\par    CHA
\par    race
\par    gender
\par    class
\par    align
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Direction Facing}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par No parameter needed.  The result is an integer: 0=north; 1=east; 2=south; 3=west.  Numbers are used so you can easily determine which direction is to the right, left, or rear
 by adding 1, 3, or 2 and then taking the remainder modulo 4.  (Or doing a bitwise AND with the integer 3.)
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Level ASL}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter is the level number and key for an entry in the level's }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Associated String List (ASL)}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(Associated String Lists)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .  The r
esult is the value associated with that key or an empty string if no such key defined.
\par 
\par The parameter is of the following form:
\par /level/key
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Temporary ASL}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter is the key for an entry in the temporary }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Associated String List (ASL)}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(Associated String Lists)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
.  The result is the value associated with that key or an empty string if no such key is defined.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Quest Stage}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter is the name of the quest.  The result is the integer stage.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 NPC List}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par No parameter.  The result is a list of names and indexes of NPCs in the party.  Each has the format "slash name slash index slash".  For example:
\par    }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 "/Alex/0//Jon/1//Peter/2/"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Character Attribute}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The parameter specifies both the character and the name of the attribute.  The character selection is first and is contained in parentheses.  There are three ways of specifying the character:
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab By number.  For example:   (^3)
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab By name.  For example:   (Gothmog)
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab The active character.   (^)
\par If Gothmog were the second character and highlighted then the complete parameter for obtaining his attribute named 'height' might look like any of the following:
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab (^2)height
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab (Gothmog)height
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab (^)height
\par If no parethesized selection appears before the attribute name then the active character is assumed.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Wiggle}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par Use this input type to specify a subfield matched by a previous GREP expression.  The parameter is the subfield number.  For example, let us say that in Gate-C you searched the text:
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405    "(X,3,7)(Y,8,2)(Z,1,3)"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par using the GREP expression
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405    "\\(Y,([0-9]+),([0-9]+)\\)"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par The intent is to capture the two numeric values associated with the entry in the list which is named 'Y'.  Here the two numeric values to be captured are surrouned by parentheses. The first will be called subfie
ld 1 and the second will be called subfield two.  Specifying 'Wiggle' with parameter "1" in input block D will result in "8" and using 'Wiggle' with parameter "2" in input block G will result in "2".  Remember that the blocks in the LogicBlock event are e
valuated in alphabetic order!
\par 
\par Why is this input-type called 'Wiggle'?  Private joke.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 GPDL Function}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par This is really adding insult to injury for those of you who think that things are already too complicated.  But here it is and it is another powerful tool.  In a nutshell....You write a GPDL function that returns a value and that value is the value of the
 Logic Block input.  The
\par function has the form:
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par    $PUBLIC FUNC input (A,B,C,D,E,F) \{ .......\} input;}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par But you only have to write the '.......' part; the rest will be provided free of charge by the Logic Block Editor.
\par 
\par The formal parameters A through F will be set to the current values of the pieces of the Logic Block of the same names so that your GPDL function can reference the other values in the Logic Block.  Wow!  Now you can do anything.
\par 
\par So, let us say you wanted to write a function that returned the value of input A if input B was equal to "x67", else "buzzz".  You would select 'GPDL Function' as the input-type and in the parameter area you might write:
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405   $IF(B=="x67")\{$RETURN A;\}; $RETURN "buzzz";}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par The ampersand substitution does not work in the parameter field of this input block.  However, the values of all the previously computed blocks are available to the GPDL function via its formal parameters 'A' through 'F'.
\par 
\par All done.  That was not so hard.  Was it?  If it appears useful but you cannot figure it out then please ask the development team for help.  It is no good if you can't use it.
\par 
\par 
