\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Level Associated String List}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par As with any Associated String List (ASL), you are welcome to add entries to the list of entries on each level of your design.  You might add an entry named "Familiar with Level" if the party has visited all the zones on the level, for example.
\par 
\par There are some special aentries that can affect the placement of walls and the blockages (can the party pass
 through?) on a level.  The keys of these entries contain the x- and y-coordinates of the wall and the side of the room the wall is on.  The keys are:
\par 
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab "$Wall,x,y,dir"
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab "$Block,x,y,dir"
\par 
\par The value of the $Wall,x,y,dir is the slot number of the wall that should appear at that position.  The value of the $Block,x,y,dir is the literal "OpenBlk" if the party can pass through the wall.  The dir part of the name is "N", "E", "S", or "W".
\par 
\par Example:
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab $Wall,5,3,E=0
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab $Block,5,3,E=OpenBlk
\par 
\par These two ASL entries w
ould make the east wall of cell 5,3 disappear and become passable to the party.  If these two entriess were later deleted then the original wall (if any) and the original blockage as specified during the design of the game would become the default.
\par 
\par Attributes such as these can be manipulated at runtime using the }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Logic Block event}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(Logic Block Event)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  or a }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 GPDL}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
!ALink(GPDL)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  script.
