\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Spell Attributes}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par When you add a spell attribute, you will see the following dialog.
\par 
\par \{bmc images\\SpellAttributes.bmp\} 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Attribute Affected:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  This is a list of all possible attributes that you can select from. Read-Only attributes are not included.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Change:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  This }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 DICEPLUS}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !KLink(DicePlus)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
 field indicates the total modification made to the selected attribute. If you check the 'Delta' box, then the
 modification will be a literal delta made to the existing attribute value. If you check the 'Percent' box, then the modification will be a percentage of the current attribute value. If you check 'Absolute', then the modification will become the current v
alue for the attribute.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Affects Who:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  Indicates who receives the attribute modification. If 'Target', then the spell target attributes are changed. Only the Target option is currently supported.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Cumulative:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  If checked, then the modifications made are cumul
ative with other attribute modifications currently in effect for the same attribute. If not checked, then this attribute modification will be ignored when the spell is cast. 
\par 
\par Example: Assume two spells that both modify $CHAR_THACO, Spell A enables cumulative, Spell B does not.
\par 
\par Scenario 1: Spell A is cast first, then Spell B.
\par Result: First $CHAR_THACO modification is made, second one is not.
\par 
\par Scenario 2: Spell B is cast first, then Spell A.
\par Result: First $CHAR_THACO modification is made, and second one is also made since it is cumulative.
\par 
\par This option only affects an individual attribute modification. If a spell modifies other attributes they will be decided upon individually.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Conditional Activation Script:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par In this text box you can type a script that will be evaluated when the spell is cast. All scripts must return 0 for failure and 1 for success. If 1 is returned, then the attribute modification will be allowed. If 0 is returned then the mod
ification will be ignored. The script does not need to be used, it is optional. If no script is present the spell will perform the indicated attribute modification unconditionally. You can substitute the keywords 'true' and 'false' for '1' and '0'.
\par 
\par As an example, suppose you want to modify an attribute only if the spell target is an }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Elf}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !KLink(Race Values)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . Then you can enter this script: 
\par 
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par    $IF ($Race($Target())=="Elf") 
\par    \{
\par       $RETURN true;
\par    \}
\par    $ELSE
\par    \{ 
\par      $RETURN false;
\par    \};
\par }{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par or more simply
\par 
\par }{\f5\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par    $RETURN ($Race($Target())=="Elf");
\par }{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 'Change By' Modification Script:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par In this text box you can type a script that will be evaluated and used to modify the DICEPLUS value in the 'Change By' box. This script can return any value. Wha
tever is returned will be added to the value computed for 'Change By'. You can query the current 'Change By' value using the script function $CURR_CHANGE_BY_VAL.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Saving Throw Modification Script:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par In this text box you can type a GPDL script that will be ev
aluated when the spell target's saving throw is computed. The value returned from this script will be added to the saving throw roll (1d20). This script will have no effect if the spell is configured not to use a saving throw.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Script Function List:}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par This i
s a list of all GPDL functions that can be used in a spell script. Each line indicates the function name, return type, and proper number of parameter types. Remember that GPDL treats all values as text strings, so even though a function returns a string i
t may still be thought of as a number. For instance, the AlignmentGood function will return a "1" or "0" based on the alignment of the character being queried.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb50\sa50\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \page }{\cs18\super\insrsid5405\charrsid5405 ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
