\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Database Object Names}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Database objects such as spells, items, and monsters must have unique names.  This is an absolute necessity if references between the databases are to work.  For example:
\par 
\par Let us say that an item called a "Wand of Zapping" is capable of creating a "Green Fire" spell.  The items database entry for the wand will name the spell and if the name is not unique then the wrong spell will be invoked.
\par 
\par It is often desirable to have multiple items (or perhaps spells or mo
nsters) that have the same name and appear to the player to be identical.  For example, one "Wand" may be capable of healing while another "Wand" is not.  So the names the player sees must be the same.  In order for the designer of the game to distinguish
 between objects of the same name a qualifier may be added to the name.
\par 
\par A qualified object name is formed as follows:
\par 
\par   objectname|qualifier
\par 
\par The qualifier is maintained in the database files but is dropped by the runtime game engine.  The player never sees the qualifier.  So the designer is free to create as many "Wand"s as seems appropriate:
\par 
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Wand
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Wand|healing
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Wand|greenfire
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Wand|youth
\par 
\par will all appear to the player as simply "Wand". Note that the separator used here is the vertical pipe, ASCII 124=0x7C.
\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\sb50\sa50\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \page }{\cs18\super\insrsid5405\charrsid5405 ${\footnote\ftnalt \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
