\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Add Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Pressing the "Add" button causes a new item to be created with the name "New Item" and default characteristics.  An edit dialog will appear with an "OK" and "Cancel" button.  Pressing the "Cancel" button cancels your request to add the item an
d pressing the "OK" button adds the new item to the }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 editor's internal database}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(InternalDatabase)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .
\par 
\par Before you add the new item by pressing "OK" you will probably want to change some of the default characteristics but you should, at the very least, change its name to a }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 name that is unique}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
!ALink(DatabaseObjectNames)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  among items.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Edit Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par To edit an e
xisting item, select it from the list of items by clicking on its name (the selected item will be highlighted) and then pressing the "Edit" button.  The edit window showing the characteristics of the item will appear, along with an "OK" button and a "Canc
el" button.  Pressing "OK" incorporates your changes and pressing "Cancel" throws your changes into the bit bucket.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Delete Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par To delete an existing item, select it from the list of items by clicking on its name (the selected item will be highlighted) 
and then pressing the "Delete" button.  The deletion is rather permanent.  Be careful.  The only way to get the item back is to cancel all the editing you have done since opening the "Items Editor" window.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 OK Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Pressing the "OK" button means that you wish to accept all the changes you have made to the items database and file them away in the editor's internal data structures.
