\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Editing Monsters Database}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par The "Edit Monsters" option of the "Database" menu provides a means of viewing the names and characteristics of the monster data currently present in the editor's internal monster database.  It is this database that will be written to the gam
e design folder and named "Monster.dat".
\par 
\par In actuality, you are editing a temporary copy of the monsters database and it will only become the permanent, working copy when you press the "OK" button".
\par 
\par When you first select the "Edit Monsters" option you will see a list of all the monsters along with five buttons:
\par 
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Add - Create a new monster
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Edit - Modify an existing monster
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Delete - Delete and existing monster
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab OK - Save changes and terminate monster edit
\par }{\f3\fs18\insrsid5405 \'b7}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 \tab Cancel - Discard changes and terminate monster edit
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Add Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Pressing the "Add" button causes a new monster to be created with the name "New Monster" and default characteristics.  An edit dialog will appear with an "OK" and "Cancel" button.
  Pressing the "Cancel" button cancels your request to add the monster and pressing the "OK" button adds the new monster to the }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 editor's internal database}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !ALink(InternalDatabase)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .

\par 
\par Before you add the new monster by pressing "OK" you will probably want to change some of the default characteristics but you should, at the very least, change its name to a }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 name that is unique}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
!ALink(DatabaseObjectNames)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  among monsters.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Edit Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par To edit an existing monster, select it from the list of monsters by clicking on i
ts name (the selected item will be highlighted) and then pressing the "Edit" button.  The edit window showing the characteristics of the monster will appear, along with an "OK" button and a "Cancel" button.  Pressing "OK" incorporates your changes and pre
ssing "Cancel" throws your changes into the bit bucket.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Delete Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par To delete an existing monster, select it from the list of monsters by clicking on its name (the selected item will be highlighted) and then pressing the "Delete" button.  The deletion i
s rather permanent.  Be careful.  The only way to get the monster back is to cancel all the editing you have done since opening the "Monster Editor" window.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 OK Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Pressing the "OK" button means that you wish to accept all the changes you have made to the monsters database and file them away in the editor's internal data structures.
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs18\cf6\insrsid5405 Cancel Button}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Pressing the "Cancel" button means that any changes you have made to any of the monsters since you opened this "Edit Monsters" window will be lost.  Be careful.
