\par }\pard \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Designing an Adventure}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par You will be the Dungeon Master in this adventure you are going to create. So you will need places, where the party can go, and events that will happen in these places. The party will meet NPC's (Non-Player-Characters). The Dungeon Master controls the acti
ons of these NPC's whereas the player will control the actions of the party.
\par  
\par Some NPC's will join the party on their quest, some will just provide information or interact with the party and some will only fight the party. 
\par Also some art will be needed to represent those places and NPC's.
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Places}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Your new design may include up to 255 different places which are called dungeons or overlands. Each dungeon and overland region is described by a map which you create and modify in the editor. The map grid for }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 1}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  is currently shown in the right black and white square. 
\par 
\par One level can be as big as 100 x 100 squares. You can place doors and walls and backdrops into the squares of the map, thus building up a town or a wilderness for the player's party to explore. 
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Events}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par In some map squares, you may want to place specific events. You can choose from a wide variety of pre-defined types of events. Each type - a combat encounter, a text statement, a treasure discovery and so on - is specified by filling in a brie
f questionnaire in the event mode. Each questionnaire poses a set of related questions about one type of event. Which monster does the party fight? What text should the player see? How much treasure does the party discover? Just insert the parts of a ques
tionnaire that need answers for the specific event you wish to design. 
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Characters}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Any monsters or NPCs encountered during an event are specified in the }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 Monster Editor}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 !KLink(Editing Monsters Database)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
.  You have just to fill in the properties for the Monster or NPC. The properties are the attributes such as the character's race, ability, class, or alignment. Also the sounds the character makes at hit, or miss, or move, the combat icon that is displaye
d during combat and the items, if any, the character  possesses. There are already several predefined monsters and NPCs. You can use them or edit them or just add a new one.
\par 
\par 
\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Art}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Drawing a map, planning an event, or creating a special character generally 
includes making decisions about what art to display on the computer screen. Some types of art are used to show the background as the player's party moves, or as it engages in combat in a dungeon or an overland region. This art consists of various sets of 
walls, floors and ceilings, as well as overland regions and combat terrain. Other types of art, such as pictures and combat icons, are used to illustrate events and to depict characters. 
\par 
\par You can load any picture in the supported formats into the appropria
te slots. They just have to have the right size to get displayed properly. For walls you need several different views. Currently DC supports four different types of walls, all of them are defined in the config.txt. Templates for two of these types are sup
plied with the DC setup, the third type is created by Phalzyr's Easywalltex program. You can even define your own type of wall by inserting the appropriate coordinates into the }{\f1\fs18\uldb\insrsid5405 config.txt}{\v\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
!KLink(Config File)}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . After choosing the appropriate wall image DC should automatically recognize the wall type.
