\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Constructing Places}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par Each adventure level defines its own two-dimensional grid, or map, at least 10 by 10 squares in size. A square is one portion of a dungeon or overland region just large enough to contain the party. As in most }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Gold Box}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  games, the party is always located in a particular map square in the current dungeon or overland region.
\par 
\par The map editor displays also a }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 3D-view}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  of the current level. You edit the map of the current level by "drawing" on it with an imaginary pen. When you
 select new attributes for various map features, such as corridor walls or ceilings, this changes pens: drawing on the map now has a different effect than before. To draw, you simply click with the mouse into the map grid directly or on one of the three b
uttons named "Left", "Front Wall"/"Place...", and "Right". This transfers the current pen settings to that particular square, replacing whatever was there before.
\par 
