\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Building an Event Chain}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par This chapter emphasizes some later steps in the design process: The repetitive cycle of modifying one existing level of your design, testing those modifications and then modifying that level again. When this
 cycle eventually finishes you will have completed another dungeon or overland region in your adventure.
\par 
\par You will now learn how to link one event to another so the second happens immediately after the first. You will also practice editing the resulting chain of events.
\par 
\par Now that you inserted a text statement, maybe you want the player to decide if the party should enter that special room. Why not inserting a short question to let the player make this decision?
\par 
\par Make sure that you are still in }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Event Mode}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  and click at the white square you inserted on your map. The }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Event Viewer}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  will open again, showing your }{
\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Text Statement}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  and its location. The }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Add}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -button under the event tree has changed and says now }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Edit}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
. By clicking on that button you could change your existing event.
\par 
\par Now first of all, if you went around in that room and came back to the door, you surely saw tha
t the event you created was repeated again and again. This can get a bit annoying, since the party already knows that this room is special. Therefore you should change the logics of this event a bit. Mark the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Text Statement}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  by left-clicking once with your mouse. Now select the option }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Once Only}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  on the right. Now your event should only fire once and never again.
\par 
\par And now you are going to chain a }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Question Yes/No}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  event.
\par 
\par To insert an event you should first click on the small }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 +}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -symbol in front of your }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Text Statement}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  in the event tree. The tree should expand and show the text }{
\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Normal Chain: No Event"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . Mark this text, choose the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Question Yes/No}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  event in the event type list and click on the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Add}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -button again. A new questionnaire opens. For "Player Sees" choose the same portrait you added before.
\par 
\par Place the text of the question into the "Player reads" field. You could for example write }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Do you want to enter this room?"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par The player has to make a choice now. So you will have to provide an answer for both possibilities. If the player selects }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 yes}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 , you could add a text like }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Welcome strangers."}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . If the player selects }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 no}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 , the text could be }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Then leave immediately, please."}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . For the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 no}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -chain the option }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Backup One Step}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  in the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 After Chain}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
" selection would be a good thing. Now that everything is filled out, select OK to return to the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Event Viewer}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .
\par 
\par The event tree has changed. Now you can see below the initial }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Text Statement}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  a chained statement called }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Normal Chain: Question Yes/No}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . If you 
expand the event tree by clicking on the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 +}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -symbol of the second event, you will notice that there are now 3 optional chains to insert events: }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Normal Chain, Yes Chain}{
\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  and }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 No Chain}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . Since you marked the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 No Chain}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  with }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Backup One Step"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
 it would be futile to insert any event there. }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 "Backup One Step"}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  takes the party into the square behind the current position. 
\par 
\par Now this is an aspect to keep in mind. The party would never be able to leave the room again if the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Question}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  event would always take place, since the pl
ayer would surely press "No" if he wants to leave the room and then the party would be pushed back a square. So it might be a good idea to have the party facing the correct direction to trigger this event. To do this, mark the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
Question Yes/No}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 -event by left-clicking on it and put the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Event Trigger}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  on }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Facing dir, only when arrive}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . Notice that now the field }{
\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Facing}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  was activated. Select the correct direction (in our Example }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 East}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 ) and click on }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Close}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  to leave the }{
\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Event Viewer}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .
\par 
\par Save the design and test your new event like before. The first }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Text Statement}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  should fire only once whereas the question should occur every time you enter the room.
\par 
\par If you want to change something in the texts or if you want to add a new event you can always go back, mark the event you wan
t to change and press "Edit" or "Insert". This way you can have a long chain of events, taking place in this one square. The different event types and their different triggers are all explained in the help files.
