\par }{\b\f1\fs18\cf17\insrsid5405 Linking Levels in a Design}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
\par 
\par So far, you have seen how to modify only one adventure level - your sample dungeon. If your adventure design is to extend beyond this dungeon, you will need a way to link two levels together. You will accomplish this with the same feature you just used fo
r the transfer in your module. 
\par 
\par To link your dungeon to another level, just place a }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Transfer Module}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  somewhere in your sample dungeon (for example at 0,0). But instead of choosing }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 1}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
 in the }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Teleport Data}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 , you use for example }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 3}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 . Probably you noticed that }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 3}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
 has currently a width and height of 0. So before you can test the transfer module, you will have to define }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 3}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 .
\par 
\par Just open the }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level List}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405  (with }{\b\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 CRTL+L}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 ), write a new name, set the height and width and leave by opening }{\i\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 Level 1}{\f1\fs18\insrsid5405 
 once more. 
\par 
\par Now save all and you are ready to test the transfer module.
